i## Configuring IPv6		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOur goal is to assign IPv6 to ESXi and IPv4 to VMs. However, ESXi's		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iweb interface fails to save network settings properly, requiring CLI		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ioperations:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Log into ESXi, enable IPv6 and reboot:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  esxcli network ip set -e true		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Enable IPv6 on the default NIC:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  esxcli network ip interface ipv6 set -e true -r false -i vmk0		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Assuming your server's IPv6 is `2001:41d0:1:234::1` , your gateway		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   is `2001:41d0:1:2ff:ff:ff:ff:ff` (refer to Kimsufi's IPv6		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   tutorials). Add two IPv6 addresses: your assigned IP and a random		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   address in the same /64 subnet to allow gateway recognition:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  esxcli network ip interface ipv6 address add -i vmk0 -I 2001:41d0:1:234::1		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  esxcli network ip interface ipv6 address add -i vmk0 -I 2001:41d0:1:2ff:12:34:56:78		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Set default gateway:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  esxcli network ip route ipv6 add -g 2001:41d0:1:2ff:ff:ff:ff:ff -n default		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Ping from another IPv6-enabled VPS to confirm connectivity before		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   proceeding.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. If your local network lacks IPv6, consider using Cloudflare to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   proxy the server's IPv6 address for easier management.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Installing Software Router		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iI use pfSense as the software router. First download the pfSense ISO		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito ESXi (HTTP supported, no proxy needed):		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  cd /vmfs/volumes/datastore1		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  wget http://frafiles.pfsense.org/mirror/downloads/pfSense-CE-2.4.3-RELEASE-amd64.iso.gz		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  gunzip pfSense-CE-2.4.3-RELEASE-amd64.iso.gz		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn the web panel:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Go to Networking > Virtual Switches, create a new vSwitch.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under Port Groups, create a port group connected to this switch (this		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  will be the internal network for VMs):		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  To allow ESXi to join the internal network:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Create another port group connected to the same switch:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Under VMkernel NICs, create a virtual NIC connected to this port		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  group with "Management" service:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Copy the physical NIC's MAC address from the Physical NICs page.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Since the datacenter binds IPs to MACs, we'll configure the VM to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  spoof the server's MAC address.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iCreate the VM normally. Note:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Set the first NIC's MAC to match the physical NIC, connecting it to "VM		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Network" (external network).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- If connected via IPv4, ESXi management will disconnect briefly when		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  the router boots (normal during IP conflict).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- The router can now ping externally but TCP connections will reset.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Next, disable ESXi's IPv4 to resolve the conflict.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Disabling IPv4		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i⚠️ High-risk operation! If IPv6 isn't working and IPv4 is disabled,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ithe server becomes inaccessible (requires reinstall)! Double-check		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIPv6 functionality first!		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFrom an IPv6-enabled VPS, SSH into the server and run:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  esxcli network ip interface ipv4 set -i vmk0 -t none		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe software router should now have normal internet access.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTo connect ESXi to the internal network:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
